<br>
It all depends on your guild focus.   If your focus is relaxed raiding, a points system will do you well.<br>
<br>
If your focus is hardcore raiding, or on the other end, rarely raiding at all, then you may want to go with a different type of system.<br>
<br>
How big is the guild?  50? 100 members?  200?  300+...<br>
<br>
Are raids mandatory?  Some mandatory and some not? Etc etc.<br>
<br>
<br>
I personally like how we handle loot within my guild.  We track attendance for official raids, and official items are the only items that count against your evaluation.  Unofficial raids, which seem to happen every night lately, are sometimes tracked and sometimes not, and anything awarded then doesn't impact an official standing.<br>
<br>
It encourages both types of raiding.  The people that want to raid every night can, and the people that only want to or only can  do the 3 or 4 official runs a week can do so knowing that what goes on outside those times is seperate from the official things in all resepcts.<br>
<br>
<br>
There's lots of different things in our looting system all developed over the past year.   Total hours are tracked, and total items looted.   Some items are booby (obtainable by 1 or 2 groups) and do not go on official evaluations even if gotten on official raids.   Some item slots are &quot;upgradeable&quot; for all classes (melee 1 and 2) to encourage minor weapon upgrade looting rather than holding out for &quot;the best&quot; and letting some weapons rot.  When you get a better weapon or shield it will take the place of your previous one on your eval.<br>
<br>
We also have a &quot;wish list&quot; system, where we allow people to make a list of 5 items they &quot;Really want&quot;, and at 150 hours of raiding then each 100 thereafter, they may put in for an item as a &quot;wish&quot; item for a good boost in their ratio, so, for example someone at 30 on the eval asking for something non wish list, while someone 50 on the eval (lower) asking for it as a wish list item, the person at 50 would likely get it.   Someone at 10 on the eval asking for something non wish list, and someone at 90 asking for something wish list, might end up with the item going to the non wish list person.  Wish list usage is restricted to those with 40% attendance or more over the last 60 days.  If you have less, you may not use these &quot;points&quot; even if you have them saved, until you pull your average over that 40% mark.  There is a +1 wish list item bonus per year in guild.<br>
<br>
Ultimately the final decision is handled by an officer vote from those on at the time.  Names are submitted by class leaders from which the officers choose someone.  Often it is unanimous, and sometimes we end up arguing... errr... discussing : ) who should get the item for 15 minutes.<br>
<br>
Each officer uses their own set of criteria for their voting which may or may not include (in no particular order)<br>
<br>
Time in Guild<br>
Loot / Raid time ratio<br>
Last item received<br>
Attendance percentage over the last 60 days<br>
Quality of upgrade<br>
Attitude / Attentiveness of the individual in and out of raids<br>
Quality of loot received in past (does someone have two tier 3 POP items and an Arch Lich item (good items) compared to someone with 2 items from the High Priest cycle in CoD and a guild hand me down? (&quot;ok&quot; items))<br>
Application to the class (should this 100 hp and mana neck with mana preservation 4 go to the warrior or the cleric?)<br>
etc etc.<br>
<br>
<br>
Anything that nobody asks for goes into the sellable pile or it rots.   Droppable things may be returned to guild later and removed from the eval, though, and thus the guild rarely, if ever, has any sellables.  Once sellable things are sold if and when we get them, the cash is turned into peridots or emeralds or whatnot and distributed, or plat is given to the class leader to distribute to the classes that use components for their spells.<br>
<br>
<br>
We have no bonus for officers or class leaders.<br>
<br>
<br>
And yes, I do like our system.  It's a bit of everything, and not a pure DKP system where a warrior might get the first Fennin Ro 18 / 19 dagger because he has hoarded all his points.<br>
<br>
<br>
And yes... we make mistakes.  No system is perfect. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aeaolena>Aeaolena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/3/03 10:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://frustrated.com/images/aeaolena.gif height=160 width=80></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How does your guild handle points? and do U agree?</span><hr size=1> I like the point system the best.<br>
<br>
Yes, in the point system we use you 'can' see your guildies points - this has never been a problem.  I'm not exactly sure how you are doing the auctions, but we use a silent auction.  An officer auctions it for a set amt of time (30 sec), people send that person tells of how much they bid, and it goes to the highest bidder for what the runner up paid + 1.  Since the updated database of how many points each person has is out in the open..people who are lazy can just ask those who are browzing the point page &quot;Hey, can you tell me my total please?&quot;<br>
<br>
I <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>do</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> feel a points system benefits a raiding guild the most; it cuts out the 'clique' or 'favoritism' factor.  You got the points, you earned it, its yours.  People who raid more generally get more loot(which helps the guild), but casual players can still save up for that dream item they really want.  Not all hope is lost, and your not depending on how much officer_2 likes you, or how great your dice are.  Also, there are some items that are just crazy to determine what class they would work best for.   What about a 35ac 10wis/int 100hp/mana 10allresists effect: haste bracer?  Warrior loot? Or cleric?   You cant tell people what their goals are and how to play their characters.  Some Enchanters go for INT, some prefer CHA or HP items.<br>
<br>
As far as officers getting more points <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>per hour</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, the idea leaves my stomach in a knot.  I just cant imagine how much tention that might create over a long period of time.  If your system is set up where points = merit to the guild; then decide exactly how much time you require your officers/leaders to be online per week to handle issues - and award bonus's weekly according to that.   <br>
<br>
This may be difficult to do depending on how difficult the positions are and how much you raid.  I might suggest something very small.  Like one hour of points per week bonus to your officers, a half hour of points per week to your leaders or whatnot.  Most in the guild should be able to recognize that your leaders/officers probably spend on average about a half-hour/hour sending tells and handling small issues weekly and not feel cheated for a little extra being given to merit their work.  <br>
<br>
