Let me see if I can put it in a way that makes sense. If you have a total of 10 BP upgrades available to the guild in a 3 month period, all of which are within the same ball park of usefulness but perhaps some have a clicky effect that is desireable or resists or some other nice to have but not have to have characteristic.<br>
<br>
Now, a DKP system could very easily create a situation where those 10 BPs actually end up in the hands of 5 or 6 people, because they raid the most, they have a back log of raid points, and there are no penalties or disadvantages for them to take as many loots as they want as long as they have points. So of those 5 or 6 people, they might see small advantages to this or that upgrade, loot one in one raid, loot another in the next raid and destroy the first.<br>
<br>
Rather than having 10 high caliber BPs spread around your guild members, you end up with say 6. You've lost the advantage of 4 of those BPs, while still being perfectly fair. If this concept doesn't bother you, then you'll see nothing wrong with DKP.<br>
-- Glatius2<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
While DKP rewards the people who raids the most, this does not always result in the best possible distribution for the guild. Sure, it probably all works out over time and in the Long Run everything is balanced and all.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In the Long Run, we'll all be dead.<br>
-- J.M. Kaynes<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
